  "thumbnail": "https://i.ytimg.com/vi/GuMVcpUWgBE/maxresdefault.jpg",
  "description": "#computer #gemini #anthropic #aiagents #systemdesign #coding #python #backendengineering #evaluation \n\nDemystifying Evals for AI Agents. Learn how to stop reacting to bugs and start building reliable, production-ready AI agents. We break down the anatomy of an eval from first principles, comparing code-based, model-based (LLM-as-a-judge), and human graders. See real-world testing strategies for Coding, Conversational, Research, and Computer Use agents using tools like Promptfoo, LangSmith, and Braintrust.\n\nWhat exactly is an AI eval?\n\nWhy are evals critical for production-ready agents?\n\nWhat is the difference between reactive and proactive agent development?\n\nWhat are the four core parts of an eval's anatomy?\n\nHow do deterministic, code-based graders work?\n\nWhat is \"LLM-as-a-judge\" (model-based grading)?\n\nWhy are human graders still considered the gold standard?\n\nHow do you properly evaluate a coding agent?\n\nWhat is SWE-bench used for?\n\nWhich metrics matter most for conversational agents?\n\nWhat is a groundedness check for research agents?\n\nHow do you prevent hallucination in agent outputs?\n\nHow do you test computer-use or web-browsing agents?\n\nWhat is the WebArena benchmark?\n\nWhen should you use Promptfoo?\n\nWhat are Braintrust and LangSmith used for?\n\nHow does Langfuse help with agent observability?\n\nWhy should you start with only 20-50 failure cases?\n\nWhy is it better to grade final outcomes rather than the agent's exact path?\n\nWhy is reading agent transcripts the most important step?\n\nTags\n#AIAgents #LLM #Evals #AIEngineering  #llm  #openai",
